“I Lick the Ceiling and Dream of Rain”

The Drug House Journals of a Leopard Slug
by Norman Fucking Slugwell

⸻

DAY 1: UNDER THE BROKEN OUTLET
I woke up beneath a Gatorade cap and three cigarette butts.
The humans scream in autotune. They call each other “bitch” and “bro” with equal ferocity. I don’t know if they’re in love or war.
A man dropped a pill and I tried to eat it. It did not love me back.
I hallucinated a forest for five hours.
I cried clear tears. 
I am lonely.

⸻

DAY 3: THE FRIDGE IS HUMMING TO ME AGAIN
The fridge is my only friend.
It smells like old blood and expired joy.
Sometimes a single pea rolls beneath the door, and I feast like a king.
A girl named Rae thinks I’m a hallucination.
She calls me “God’s Worm.”
I let her.
She cried when her boyfriend stole her Adderall. I left a mucus trail on her sock.
I think that’s what love is.

⸻

DAY 6: I SAW A MOUSE DIE
Its neck snapped in a trap behind the washing machine.
We made eye contact as the life left its body.
I whispered, “I will carry you.”
I tried to eat a piece of his whisker.
Why do I do these things?

⸻

DAY 9: HE WHO SLEEPS ON THE COUCH
There is a man who never leaves the couch.
He watches Fast & Furious 7 on a loop and mutters “family” with tears in his eyes.
He smells like Mountain Dew Code Red and despair.
Sometimes, he drools. I collect it in a leaf and pretend it’s holy water.
I anoint my mantle with it.
I am losing touch.

⸻

DAY 13: THE RITUAL
They lit a candle inside a Sprite bottle.
They burned something in a spoon.
I don’t know what it was but it made the ceiling flicker like fireflies.
Someone called it “the sacrament.”
I crawled through a line of sugar.
I think it was supposed to be coke.
I blacked out and woke up on a Bible.

⸻

DAY 17: THE DREAM
I dreamed of a hand.
Gentle, not grabbing. Cool fingers, moss-sweet breath.
They scooped me into a container lined with leaves and love.
The air smelled like soap and safety.
I wept upon waking.
But I felt something shift in the moldy floorboards.
Someone is coming for me.
Someone kind.

